<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-081-274 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 205 789</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 16 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. trade deficit drops but economy weakens.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EconomicsReportsTrade DeficitUnited States. Department of Commerce.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>U.S.andP;  TRADE DEFICIT DROPS BUT ECONOMY WEAKENS 08/16/91 WASHINGTON, DC,U.S.A., 1991 AUG 16 (NB) -- The U.S.andP;  Commerce Department has reported adecrease in the U.S.andP;  balance of trade deficit with the rest of the world,but one Washington insider has pointed out that, because of the details whichshow just how the change in the trade balance occurred, the lowered tradedeficit was actually bad news for the economy.andM;The preliminary trade deficit numbers for June are down significantly, thelowest since 1983, with imports down more than exports, showing a weak U.S.andO;consumer demand, even in the face of a climbing value of the U.S.andP;  dollarwhich tends to reduce exports because it increases the overseas price ofUS-produced goods while it also increases US buying power.andM;The national trade deficit, the difference between the amount imported versuswhat the U.S.andP;  exports, dropped to only slightly more than $4 billion forJune, leading to the projection of an annual trade deficit of only $60billion, about one-third less than the figure for 1990.andM;A drop in the deficit can be a very good thing if it is due to strong salesand strong imports, with the exports being larger than the imports.andM;The June drop in the trade deficit is disturbing because the U.S.andP;  importednearly $1.2 billion less from other countries, while American companies soldjust over $400 million less to customers in other countries, showing not onlyweak domestic demand but a shrinking export base for U.S.andP;  manufacturers.andM;The U.S.andP;  has a $1.7 billion trade surplus with Western Europe, whileU.S.-Japan trade accounted for more than $3 billion of the deficit, up over$800 million from the May numbers.andM;The biggest boosts to the trade numbers came from aircraft sales overseas anda small decrease in the cost of oil.andM;These are only preliminary numbers which may go up or down, somethingemphasized by new numbers on the May deficit, which Commerce had pegged at apreliminary $4.6 billion but which were today revised upward to $4.8 billion.andM;Other recent numbers show that industrial production was up by amore-than-expected 0.5 percent, the fourth consecutive advance, but theUniversity of Michigan's Consumer Confidence Survey was, according to earlyfigures obtained by Knight-Ridder, down about three points from July's 82.9to 79.6 for August, showing a lack of confidence in the strength of the U.S.andO;economy.andM;The confidence number is very important because when consumers lackconfidence they tend to save money rather than spend it on new goods andservices.andM;In other economic news, the Congressional Budget Office has reported that theU.S.andP;  budget deficit will continue to grow, consuming money that could beinvested to increase productivity.andM;(John McCormick/19910816)</TEXT></DOC>